title: Somalia - Subnational Population Statistics
datasetDescription:
The United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) partnered with donors and UN agencies and took up the lead role to support the Somali authorities in undertaking the Population Estimation Survey (PESS) for Somalia in October 2013- March 2014.

REFERENCE YEAR:  2014

UNFPA investigated replacement or projection of this dataset in 2021.  Only ADM0 (national) data was available.  No better alternative is currently available.

PESS gathered basic critical information on the Somalis living in urban, rural and nomadic areas (interviewed at water points during the peak of the long, dry season), and in settlements for internally displaced persons. One standard questionnaire was used in selected enumeration areas or pre-identified areas. Data was collected in three main phases: cartographic field mapping, household listing in the sampled areas, and the interviewing of households using the standard questionnaire.

PESS report by UNFPA had only the population estimate at regional level (Admin level 1). With the demand to get this data disaggregated to district level to enhance assessment and in particular assessments of people in food insecure by FAO-FSNAU, the district data was interpolated using FSNAU livelihood information embedded in the 2005 UNDP district level population data
datasetSource: Multiple Source (Humanitarian Partners)
license_title: Other

XLSX.description: Gazeteer (tabular data)

CSV.description: Somalia Admin Level 0 (Country), Admin Level 1 (Region), Admin Level 2 (District) population statistics including 2005 Rural, Urban, and total populations (source UNDP) and 2014 Rural, Urban, IDP, and Total populations (source UNFPA).

title: Georgia - Subnational Population Statistics
datasetDescription:
REFERENCE YEAR:  2019

This dataset contains population estimates for Georgia as of 1 January 2019 at country-level, including a breakdown by sex, age groups and urban and rural areas. It also contains population statistics from the 2014 census at first administrative level (mkhare/regions, Tbilisi independent city and autonomous republics), second administrative level (municipalities and independent cities), third administrative level (communities, boroughs, cities and villages) and for all populated places in the country.

All population numbers are disaggregated by sex. The population numbers are also disaggregated by age, except for the population numbers for the districts in Tbilisi (admin2), the population numbers at admin3 and the population numbers of the populated places.

Please note that these datasets do not include population numbers for the Georgian breakeaway regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.

The files each include a sheet with metadata.

The administrative level 0, 1, and 2 tables are suitable for database or GIS linkage to the [Georgia administrative level 0-2 boundaries](https://data.humdata.org/dataset/georgia-administrative-level-0-2-boundaries).
caveats:
Please note that this dataset does not include population numbers for the Georgian breakaway regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.

The population numbers for the districts in Tbilisi (at administrative level 2 and lower subdivisions) and all population numbers at administrative level 3 and for the populated places are not disaggregated by age.

There are 20 populated places within the districts of Tbilisi of which it is unclear to which admin3 level they belong.

The administrative level 0-2 gazetteer was prepared by ITOS.  An  administrative level 3 supplementary gazetteer is also provided.

methodology_other:
The 2021 population estimate employs a combination of methods and sources using the 2017 Central Statistics Agency (CSA) projection as the basis, and CSA's regional population growth rates are applied to project the 2021 estimates. The 2017 population estimate includes disaggregation by sex and urban rural population at admin level 3 (woreda). The age breakdown is estimated based on the CSA 2016 Household Consumption and Expenditure Survey (HCES) available at admin level 1 (region).

For newly created woredas outside SNNPR, population distributions from WorldPop is used to extrapolate population projections. For SNNPR, population estimate from the regional Plan Commission is used as the basis, and then corrected against the CSA regional projections for 2021.

The age groups from CSA 2016 HCES includes the age groups 0-9 and 15-19 years. To support humanitarian needs analysis and response planning for specific children age groups, the age group 0-9 has been split into two (0-4 and 5-9) and the 15-19 age group has been split into two (15-17 and 18-19). To do this, the Federal Ministry of Health's estimated population distribution for the age groups under consideration has been applied.
